Data are based on the characteristics of 150 Iris plants from three species (setosa, versicolor, and virginica) with variables describing the sepal and petal length and width.

t2_species <- iris_raw %>%
  filter(Species %in% c("setosa", "virginica")) %>%
  tbl_summary(
    by = Species,
    statistic = all_continuous() ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
    digits = all_continuous() ~ 2
  )


t2_ttest <- t2_species %>%
  add_p(test = all_continuous() ~ "t.test",
        pvalue_fun = ~ style_pvalue(.x, digits = 2)) %>%
  modify_caption("Table 2. Iris Morphological Characteristics") %>%
  modify_header(
    update = list(
      label ~ '',
      stat_1 ~ 'Setosa',
      stat_2 ~ 'Virginica',
      statistic ~ "**t-value**",
      p.value ~ '**P-value**'
    )
  )

t2_anova <- t2 %>%
  add_p(test = all_continuous() ~ "aov",
        pvalue_fun = ~ style_pvalue(.x, digits = 2)) %>%
  modify_caption("Table 2. Iris Morphological Characteristics") %>%
  modify_fmt_fun(statistic ~ style_sigfig) %>%
  modify_header(
    update = list(
      label ~ "",
      stat_1 ~ "**Setosa**",
      stat_2 ~ "**Versicolor**",
      stat_3 ~ "**Virginica**",
      statistic ~ "**F / t-value**",
      p.value ~ "**P-value**"
    )
  )

2 One-way analysis of means

Table showing the mean and a one way ANOVA test because we are comparing more than two groups which requires an ANOVA. The table shows whether there is a difference across sepal and petal lengths and widths based on the species. According to the table, there is a significant difference in lengths and widths based on species.

iris_two_species <- iris_raw %>%
  filter(Species %in% c("setosa", "virginica")) %>%
  droplevels()

t2_ancova <- iris_two_species %>%
  select(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width, Petal.Length, Petal.Width, Species) %>%
  tbl_summary(
    by = Species,
    include = c(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width, Petal.Width),
    statistic = all_continuous() ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
    digits = all_continuous() ~ 1,
    missing = "no"
  ) %>%
  add_difference(
    adj.vars = c(Petal.Length),
    pvalue_fun = ~ style_pvalue(.x, digits = 2)
  )

Quick and compact look of the overall structure of the data.

summary <- iris_raw %>%
  dplyr::select(Species, Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width, Petal.Length, Petal.Width) %>%
  mutate(
    Sepal.Length = as.numeric(Sepal.Length),
    Sepal.Width = as.numeric(Sepal.Width),
    Petal.Length = as.numeric(Petal.Length),
    Petal.Width = as.numeric(Petal.Width))
t4 <- summary %>%
  tbl_summary(
  by = Species,
  type = all_continuous() ~ "continuous",
  statistic = all_continuous() ~ "{mean} ({sd})",
  digits = all_continuous() ~ 1,
  label = list(
    Sepal.Length ~ "Sepal Length (cm)",
    Sepal.Width ~ "Sepal Width (cm)",
    Petal.Length ~ "Petal Length (cm)",
    Petal.Width ~ "Petal Width (cm)"
  )
)  %>%
    
add_p(test = all_continuous() ~ "aov") %>%
  modify_header(label = "**Attribute**", 
                stat_1 = "**Setosa**",
                stat_2 = "**Versicolor**",
                stat_3 = "**Virginica**",
                p.value = "**p-value**") %>%
  modify_footnote(everything() ~ NA) %>%
  modify_caption("Table 4. Morphological Characteristics of Iris Flowers")
